description:
# Goal

Apply the NewsBlur preface settings to the NewsBlur share payload.

This task owns runtime behavior. It depends on `openrouter-summarizer-qsd.1` for settings keys/defaults.

# Current Behavior

`pageInteraction.js` currently builds NewsBlur content like this:

```js
const summaryHtml = lastSummary;
const newsblurStoryHtml = getContentArtifactText(
  lastContentArtifacts,
  CONTENT_ARTIFACT_KEYS.NEWSBLUR_STORY_HTML,
);
const combinedContent = summaryHtml + "<hr>" + newsblurStoryHtml;
```

The request payload then sends:

```js
options: {
  title,
  story_url,
  content: combinedContent,
  comments: "",
}
```

# Required New Behavior

If the option is disabled, keep current behavior exactly:

```js
content: summaryHtml + "<hr>" + newsblurStoryHtml,
```

If the option is enabled and the template is non-empty after trimming, prefix the existing content with one HTML paragraph containing the rendered preface:

```html
<p>LLM (openai/gpt-4.1-mini) says:</p>
<ul>...</ul>
<hr>
<article>...</article>
```

# Placeholder Semantics

Support this placeholder token:

```text
@LLMNAME@
```

Replace every occurrence with the active summary model name.

Example:

```js
const template = "LLM (@LLMNAME@) says:";
const modelName = "openai/gpt-4.1-mini";
const rendered = template.replaceAll("@LLMNAME@", modelName);
// rendered === "LLM (openai/gpt-4.1-mini) says:"
```

Use the model already tracked for the completed summary. `pageInteraction.js` stores this as `lastModelUsed` from the summary response. If no model name is available, use the same fallback the existing code uses for display context, currently `"Unknown"`.

# Security Requirement

The preface template is user-controlled setting text. Escape it before injecting into HTML.

Do not do this:

```js
return `<p>${renderedPreface}</p>${combinedContent}`;
```

Do this behavior instead:

```js
return `<p>${escapeHtml(renderedPreface)}</p>${combinedContent}`;
```

A minimal helper contract is:

```js
const escapeHtml = (value) => String(value)
  .replaceAll("&", "&amp;")
  .replaceAll("<", "&lt;")
  .replaceAll(">", "&gt;")
  .replaceAll('"', "&quot;")
  .replaceAll("'", "&#39;");
```

Use an existing sanitizer/escaping helper if one already exists. Do not add a broad sanitizer dependency just for a text line.

# Suggested Helper

Prefer extracting the content builder to a pure helper so the behavior can be tested without browser globals:

```js
export const NEWSBLUR_PREFACE_MODEL_TOKEN = "@LLMNAME@";

export const buildNewsblurShareContent = ({
  summaryHtml,
  newsblurStoryHtml,
  prefaceEnabled,
  prefaceTemplate,
  modelName,
}) => {
  const combinedContent = `${summaryHtml}<hr>${newsblurStoryHtml}`;
  const template = typeof prefaceTemplate === "string"
    ? prefaceTemplate.trim()
    : "";

  if (prefaceEnabled !== true || template === "") {
    return combinedContent;
  }

  const renderedPreface = template.replaceAll(
    NEWSBLUR_PREFACE_MODEL_TOKEN,
    modelName || "Unknown",
  );

  return `<p>${escapeHtml(renderedPreface)}</p>${combinedContent}`;
};
```

The helper can live wherever the codebase pattern fits best. Good candidates are a small content/share helper near `pageInteraction.js` or an integration-adjacent helper if tests already target that area.

# Joplin Dual-Share Review

Current code may reuse `combinedContent` when “also send to Joplin” is checked:

```js
JoplinManager.fetchAndShowNotebookSelection(
  combinedContent,
  story_url,
  true,
);
```

The requested feature is phrased as “When sharing to newsblur”. Therefore:

- Apply the preface to the NewsBlur payload.
- Do not silently apply it to Joplin unless product behavior is made explicit and covered by tests.
- If both integrations need separate payload variables, use clear names such as `newsblurContent` and `joplinContent`.

# Goal

Add focused regression coverage for the optional NewsBlur preface feature.

This task should fail against the old behavior and pass after the implementation tasks are complete.

# Required Coverage Areas

## Settings Schema Defaults

Add or update settings schema tests to prove the option is off by default:

```js
assert.equal(
  UI_SAFE_SETTINGS_DEFAULTS.newsblurSharePrefaceEnabled,
  false,
);
assert.equal(
  UI_SAFE_SETTINGS_DEFAULTS.newsblurSharePrefaceTemplate,
  "",
);
```

Also verify normalized empty storage returns the same defaults:

```js
const settings = normalizeSettingsForUi({});
assert.equal(settings.newsblurSharePrefaceEnabled, false);
assert.equal(settings.newsblurSharePrefaceTemplate, "");
```

## Settings Store Save/Load

Verify saved values round-trip through sync settings:

```js
await saveSettings({
  newsblurSharePrefaceEnabled: true,
  newsblurSharePrefaceTemplate: "LLM (@LLMNAME@) says:",
}, { chromeApi: chromeMock });

const settings = await loadSettings({ chromeApi: chromeMock });
assert.equal(settings.newsblurSharePrefaceEnabled, true);
assert.equal(
  settings.newsblurSharePrefaceTemplate,
  "LLM (@LLMNAME@) says:",
);
```

Use the actual exported storage key constants if the codebase requires bracketed object keys.

## Options Page Wiring

Extend the options page test harness or add a focused options test that verifies:

- `#newsblurSharePrefaceEnabled` exists.
- `#newsblurSharePrefaceTemplate` exists.
- The checkbox is unchecked on default load.
- The input is empty on default load.
- Existing token loading behavior still works and is not coupled to this setting.

Example assertions:

```js
const enabled = document.getElementById("newsblurSharePrefaceEnabled");
const template = document.getElementById("newsblurSharePrefaceTemplate");

assert.equal(enabled.checked, false);
assert.equal(template.value, "");
assert.match(
  document.body.textContent,
  /When sharing to newsblur, preface with this line:/,
);
```

## Share Content Builder

Add a pure unit test for the helper that builds the NewsBlur content.

Disabled behavior must be unchanged:

```js
assert.equal(
  buildNewsblurShareContent({
    summaryHtml: "<ul><li>Summary</li></ul>",
    newsblurStoryHtml: "<article>Story</article>",
    prefaceEnabled: false,
    prefaceTemplate: "LLM (@LLMNAME@) says:",
    modelName: "openai/gpt-4.1-mini",
  }),
  "<ul><li>Summary</li></ul><hr><article>Story</article>",
);
```

Enabled behavior must add the preface:

```js
assert.equal(
  buildNewsblurShareContent({
    summaryHtml: "<ul><li>Summary</li></ul>",
    newsblurStoryHtml: "<article>Story</article>",
    prefaceEnabled: true,
    prefaceTemplate: "LLM (@LLMNAME@) says:",
    modelName: "openai/gpt-4.1-mini",
  }),
  "<p>LLM (openai/gpt-4.1-mini) says:</p>" +
    "<ul><li>Summary</li></ul><hr><article>Story</article>",
);
```

Repeated placeholders must all be replaced:

```js
assert.match(
  buildNewsblurShareContent({
    summaryHtml: "<p>S</p>",
    newsblurStoryHtml: "<p>B</p>",
    prefaceEnabled: true,
    prefaceTemplate: "@LLMNAME@ / @LLMNAME@:",
    modelName: "model/x",
  }),
  /^<p>model\/x \/ model\/x:<\/p>/,
);
```

HTML in the template must be escaped:

```js
assert.match(
  buildNewsblurShareContent({
    summaryHtml: "<p>S</p>",
    newsblurStoryHtml: "<p>B</p>",
    prefaceEnabled: true,
    prefaceTemplate: "<script>alert(1)</script> @LLMNAME@",
    modelName: "model/x",
  }),
  /^<p>&lt;script&gt;alert\(1\)&lt;\/script&gt; model\/x<\/p>/,
);
```

# Quality Gate Expectations

Run the narrow tests touched by this feature first. Then run the project gate assigned in the verification bead.

Do not mark this bead complete with only manual inspection. The behavior is small and deterministic, so it should have automated coverage.

# Feature Brief

Add a configurable, explicitly opt-in preface line for NewsBlur shares.

The user-visible requirement is:

- In Options, near the existing NewsBlur API token controls, expose the label text:
  `When sharing to newsblur, preface with this line:`
- Provide an input box for the line/template.
- The feature must be **off by default**. A newly installed extension, migrated extension, or reset options state must not add any preface to NewsBlur shares unless the user has explicitly enabled it.
- The template must support the model placeholder `@LLMNAME@`. Example configured template:

```text
LLM (@LLMNAME@) says:
```

If the active summary model is `openai/gpt-4.1-mini`, the rendered preface text should be equivalent to:

```text
LLM (openai/gpt-4.1-mini) says:
```

# Product Behavior

The setting is not a token and is not sensitive. Store it with the other non-secret sync settings, not in encrypted token storage.

Use two settings rather than treating an empty string as the only disabled state:

```js
export const STORAGE_KEY_NEWSBLUR_SHARE_PREFACE_ENABLED =
  "newsblurSharePrefaceEnabled";
export const STORAGE_KEY_NEWSBLUR_SHARE_PREFACE_TEMPLATE =
  "newsblurSharePrefaceTemplate";
```

Default state:

```js
const DEFAULT_NEWSBLUR_SHARE_PREFACE_ENABLED = false;
const DEFAULT_NEWSBLUR_SHARE_PREFACE_TEMPLATE = "";
```

The boolean matters because the user may type and save a draft string without wanting it applied yet. The option being off must mean no preface is rendered, even if a saved template exists.

# Share Rendering Rules

The final NewsBlur `content` payload currently has this shape:

```js
const combinedContent = summaryHtml + "<hr>" + newsblurStoryHtml;
```

After this feature, the current shape remains the fallback when the option is disabled:

```js
const combinedContent = summaryHtml + "<hr>" + newsblurStoryHtml;
```

When enabled and the template is non-empty after trimming, render the escaped template before the existing content:

```js
const contentWithPreface =
  `<p>${escapeHtml(renderedPreface)}</p>` + combinedContent;
```

The implementation must escape the user-controlled preface text before adding it to HTML. Do not insert the raw template with `innerHTML` semantics. The user text comes from extension settings and must still be treated as untrusted content.

Placeholder replacement requirements:

```js
const NEWSBLUR_PREFACE_MODEL_TOKEN = "@LLMNAME@";
const renderedPreface = template.replaceAll(
  NEWSBLUR_PREFACE_MODEL_TOKEN,
  modelName || "Unknown",
);
```

`@LLMNAME@` may appear zero, one, or many times. Replace all occurrences.

# Scope Boundaries

This feature is only about NewsBlur share content. It must not change:

- NewsBlur token storage.
- OpenRouter token storage.
- Joplin token storage.
- Summary generation prompts.
- Chat prompts or chat quick prompts.
- Existing NewsBlur behavior when disabled.

Review the dual-share Joplin path. If the same `combinedContent` variable is reused for Joplin when “also send to Joplin” is checked, make the behavior intentional and documented in code/tests. The user asked for “When sharing to newsblur”, so the safest default is: the preface applies to the NewsBlur payload only unless the implementation explicitly chooses and tests shared behavior.

# Implementation Hint

A pure helper will make this easy to test:

```js
export const NEWSBLUR_PREFACE_MODEL_TOKEN = "@LLMNAME@";

export const buildNewsblurShareContent = ({
  summaryHtml,
  newsblurStoryHtml,
  prefaceEnabled,
  prefaceTemplate,
  modelName,
}) => {
  const combinedContent = `${summaryHtml}<hr>${newsblurStoryHtml}`;
  const template = typeof prefaceTemplate === "string"
    ? prefaceTemplate.trim()
    : "";

  if (prefaceEnabled !== true || template === "") {
    return combinedContent;
  }

  const renderedPreface = template.replaceAll(
    NEWSBLUR_PREFACE_MODEL_TOKEN,
    modelName || "Unknown",
  );

  return `<p>${escapeHtml(renderedPreface)}</p>${combinedContent}`;
};
```

Use existing project style and helper locations. The snippet is a behavioral contract, not a demand for a new abstraction if the codebase has a better local pattern.

## Problem
The decryptSensitiveData function in js/encryption.js (lines 66-88) returns empty string for both 'no data provided' and 'decryption failed' scenarios. Callers cannot distinguish between a missing token and a corrupted/tampered token.

## Evidence
js/encryption.js:66-67:
if (!encrypted) return '';

js/encryption.js:84-86:
} catch (e) {
  console.error('[Encryption] Decryption failed:', e);
  return '';
}

## Impact
- Security issues masked (tampering not detected)
- Data corruption not surfaced to user
- Debugging difficult - same empty result for different failures

## Fix Required
Return a result object instead of string:
{ success: boolean, data: string, error: string|null }

Update all callers (chatHandler.js, background.js) to check success before using data.

## Problem
The trackError method in js/errorHandler.js (lines 78-89) uses chrome.storage.local.get/set callbacks but never checks chrome.runtime.lastError. If storage is full or corrupted, errors are silently lost.

## Evidence
js/errorHandler.js:80-84:
chrome.storage.local.get(['errorLog'], (data) => {
  const log = data.errorLog || [];
  log.push(errorInfo);
  if (log.length > 50) log.shift();
  chrome.storage.local.set({ errorLog: log });
});

No chrome.runtime.lastError check in either callback.

## Impact
- Storage failures go unnoticed
- Error logs may be silently lost
- Debugging becomes harder when error tracking itself fails

## Fix Required
1. Check chrome.runtime.lastError after get() callback
2. Check chrome.runtime.lastError after set() callback
3. Use console.warn (not error) to log tracking failures
4. Keep outer try/catch to prevent crashes

## Problem
Various magic numbers are scattered throughout the codebase without named constants, reducing maintainability and readability.

## Evidence
- 60000 in js/chatHandler.js (controller timeout)
- 3000 in notification calls (per ADR this is intentional but should be constant)
- 65568 snippet truncation limit
- 50 max error log entries

## Action Required
Add to constants.js:
export const CONTROLLER_TIMEOUT_MS = 60000;
export const NOTIFICATION_TIMEOUT_MS = 3000;
export const SNIPPET_TRUNCATION_LIMIT = 65568;
export const MAX_ERROR_LOG_ENTRIES = 50;
export const MAX_CONTROLLERS = 100;

Update all files to import and use these constants.
